(8. Microcode inside the Intel 8087 floating-point chip: register exchange) Tj
T*
(Source: Ken Shirriff's blog | Published: 2026-05-30T10:09:35.056-07:00) Tj
T*
(Link: http://www.righto.com/2026/05/microcode-inside-intel-8087-floating.html) Tj
T*
(In 1980, Intel introduced the 8087 floating-point chip, a co-processor that made floating-point) Tj
T*
(operations up to 100 times faster. This chip was highly influential, and today most processors) Tj
T*
(use the floating-point standard introduced by the 8087. The 8087 uses complicated algorithms to) Tj
T*
(accurately compute functions such as square roots, tangents, and exponentials. These algorithms) Tj
T*
(are implemented inside the chip in low-level code called microcode. I'm part of a group, the) Tj
T*
(Opcode Collective, that is reverse-engineering this microcode. In this post, I take a close) Tj
T*
(look at the microcode for one of the 8087's instructions? FXCH ?and explain how the microcode) Tj
T*
(works. The FXCH \(Floating-point Exchange\) instruction exchanges two floating-point registers.) Tj
T*
(You might expect this instruction to be trivial, but there's more going on than you might) Tj
T*
(expect; the microcode uses 14 micro-instructions to implement the exchange instruction. The) Tj
T*
(Intel 8087 chip is packaged in a 40-pin DIP \(dual in-line package\). To explore the microcode, I) Tj
T*
(opened up an 8087 chip and created a high-resolution image with a microscope. The large) Tj
T*
(microcode ROM occupies a central position, holding the micro-instructions tha...) Tj
T*
